value.value: A bilateral type of conductive hearing impairment.
A type of hearing impairment caused by an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve with congenital onset.
A form of sensorineural hearing impairment that affects primarily the lower frequencies.
Underdevelopment of the helix, i.e., of the outer rim of the pinna.
A mild form of conductive hearing impairment.

definition.value: Conductive hearing impairment with 21-40 dB deficit.

value.value: A severe form of sensorineural hearing impairment.
The presence of calcium- and oxalate-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys.
Reduced volume of the testicle (the male gonad).
Presence of a gap in the posterior laryngotracheal wall with a continuity between the larynx and the esophagus.

definition.value: Embryologically, the trachea and esophagus share a common lumen until they are separated by the development of the tracheoesophageal septum. Failure of this fusion and incomplete development of the tracheoesophageal septum may lead to congenital abnormalities such as isolatedlaryngeal cleft, tracheoesophageal fistula, and esophageal atresia, depending on the severity of the abnormality. Patients with laryngeal cleft may present with feeding difficulty, chronic cough, stridor, pneumonia or respiratory distress, depending on the size of the cleft.

value.value: The presence of one or more obsessive-compulsive personality traits. Obsessions refer to persistent intrusive thoughts, and compulsions to intrusive behaviors, which the affected person experiences as involuntary, senseless, or repugnant.

definition.value: Obsessions have been defined as intrusive and unwanted thoughts that are subjectively experienced as unacceptable.

value.value: Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the inner ear.
A smaller than normal acetabulum that has insufficient femoral head coverage leading to abnormal hip joint contact pressures, instability and pain.

definition.value: Acetabular dysplasia can lead to hip pain and early-onset hip osteoarthritis.

value.value: Intrauterine growth retardation that is 4 or more standard deviations below average, corrected for sex and gestational age.

Impaired feeding performance of an infant as manifested by difficulties such as weak and ineffective sucking, brief bursts of sucking, and falling asleep during sucking. There may be difficulties with chewing or maintaining attention.
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short limbs but an average-sized trunk.

definition.value: A type of dwarfism (marked short stature with adult height below 147 cm) in which the limbs are disproportionately affected. Note that brachymelia is a general term referring to shortening of the limbs. Micromelia refers to the shortening of entire limbs (in contrast to rhizomelia, mesomelia, and acromelia, which refer to shortening of the proximal, middle, or distal portions of the limbs).

value.value: Slow or limited growth after birth.
Disproportionate shortening of the proximal segment of limbs (i.e. the femur and humerus).
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with onset in childhood.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period and affecting the entire musculature.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk.
An acute form of rhabdomyolysis.
Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in infancy.

definition.value: This term should not be used for new annotations. Instead, state the type of onset of hypotonia more exactly.

value.value: Progressive muscular atrophy affecting muscles in the distal portions of the extremities.
Muscular atrophy affecting proximally located muscles of the legs, i.e., of the thigh.
A type of muscle stiffness that occurs following physical exertion.
Muscle hypertrophy affecting the calf muscles.

label.value: Proximal muscle weakness in lower limbs

value.value: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the legs.

label.value: Proximal muscle weakness in upper limbs

value.value: A lack of strength of the proximal muscles of the arms.
An abnormally increased tendency towards muscle fatigue induced by physical exercise.

Weakness of the muscles responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot, that is, of the movement of the toes towards the shin. The foot dorsiflexors include the tibialis anterior, the extensor hallucis longus, the extensor digitorum longus, and the peroneus tertius muscles.

definition.value: Dorsiflexion of the foot extends the foot superiorly, as if taking the foot off the gas pedal.

value.value: Generalized weakness of the muscles of the arms and legs.
Rhabdomyolysis induced by exercise.
Atrophy of the peroneous muscles, peroneus longus (also known as Fibularis longus), Peroneus brevis (also known as fibularis brevis, and Peroneus tertius (also known as fibularis tertius).

definition.value: The peroneus muscles (longus, brevis, and tertius) originate on the fibula and insert on the metatarsals.

value.value: Reduced strength of the distal musculature of the legs.

definition.value: This finding can be due to peripheral neuropathy.

value.value: Progressively reduced strength of the distal musculature.
Generalized degenerative changes of the fat tissue.

definition.value: Impairment in the physical production of speech sounds.
Speech articulation difficulties can result from abnormalities of the vocal tract (the larynx and the pharyngeal, oral, and nasal cavities).

value.value: An abnormality of adipose tissue, which is loose connective tissue composed of adipocytes.
Degenerative changes of the fat tissue.
Muscular atrophy involving the muscles of the hand.

definition.value: This term can be used to described bilateral amyotrophy of the musculature of the hand.

value.value: Hypoplasia (congenital reduction in size) of the fifth finger, also known as the little finger.
Contractures of one ore more joints of the hands meaning chronic loss of joint motion due to structural changes in non-bony tissue.
Divergence of the longitudinal axis of the hand at the wrist in a posterior (ulnar) direction (i.e., towards the little finger).

A vestibular schwannoma (also known as acoustic neuroma, acoustic neurinoma, or acoustic neurilemoma) is a benign, usually slow-growing tumor that develops from the VIIIth cranial nerve supplying the inner ear.
